Malaysia Languages and Extinction level

Exploration of languages and extinction level in West Malaysia

We load the data from Kaggle dataset-Extinct Languages, and extract data that belongs to Malaysia, below is the legend describing the level of extinction depicted in the data.

Degree.of.Extinction Descriptions
Vulnerable most children speak the language, but it may be restricted to certain domains, e.g., home
Definitely endangered children no longer learn the language as a 'mother tongue' in the home
Severely endangered language is spoken by grandparents and older generations; while the parent generation may understand it, they do not speak it to children or among themselves
Critically endangered the youngest speakers are grandparents and older, and they speak the language partially and infrequently
Extinct there are no speakers left 
library(ggmap)
library(knitr)
ext.lang <- read.csv("../input/data.csv", stringsAsFactors = FALSE)
my<-which(ext.lang$Countries=="Malaysia")
ext.my<-ext.lang[my,]

Plot the information, focus on West Malaysia only, using terrain map to see if there’s any relationship to terrain information visually,

#Using google map
ext.my.west<-ext.my[ext.my$Longitude<105,]
map<-get_googlemap(c(102, 4), zoom=7, maptype="terrain")
ggmap(map) + geom_point(aes(x=Longitude, y=Latitude, color=Degree.of.endangerment, size=Number.of.speakers), data=ext.my.west)

The biggest bubble is near the mountain terrain, showing from table below with language that are Severely endangered (color as purple in map above), with 15000 speakers for Semai as of 2007 (Bradley)

a<-""
for(i in 1:(dim(ext.my.west)[1])) {
  l <-c(ext.my.west$Longitude[i], ext.my.west$Latitude[i])
  a[i]<-revgeocode(c(lon = l[1], lat = l[2]), output = "address", messaging = FALSE)
}
ext.my.west$State<-sapply(strsplit(a, ','), function(x) { gsub(".*\\s+([a-zA-Z]+?)$", "\\1", x[length(x)-1])} )
kable(ext.my.west[ext.my.west$Degree.of.endangerment=="Severely endangered",c(2,11, 12:14, 16)])

Exploration of languages and extinction level in East Malaysia

Let’s look into the other side of Malaysia (Sabah and Sarawak), there’s only 5 languages in the list and mostly with less than 500 speakers. Below is the map, only Sian and Punan Batu is towards inland and Sian with only 50 speakers but it is rank as Severely endangered and the parents and grandparents is still the speakers.

ext.my.east<-ext.my[ext.my$Longitude>105,]
map<-get_googlemap(c(115, 4), zoom=6, scale=1, maptype="terrain")
Source : https://maps.googleapis.com/maps/api/staticmap?center=4,115&zoom=6&size=640x640&scale=1&maptype=terrain
ggmap(map) + geom_point(aes(x=Longitude, y=Latitude, color=Degree.of.endangerment, size=Number.of.speakers), data=ext.my.east)

Summary

Initial exploration shows that language that spoken by people that is situated in mountain terrain have more speakers in Severely endangered categry versus those in the flat land. Over in Borneo (East Malaysia), the number of speakers is very low, with the highest 400 spekers of Abai Sungai and ranked as Definately endangered.
